bib_record.title: Investigation of the neutron-induced fission of 238U in the energy range 1 MeV to 500 MeV

free_txt: prelim.data
The LAMPF Meson facility supplies the
800 MeV proton beam which hits  a spallation source
in WNR for neutron production.
Weapons Neutron research Facility WNR: a
spallation source (a 7.5 cm long cylindrical tungsten
target, called 'target 4' in the thesis) is hit by the
proton beam and produces neutrons of energy
0.1-800 MeV. The facility has several flight paths of
different length and direction. The spallation source
produces neutrons and spallation products, which in
turn react with the target and this way broaden the
neutron spectrum. Neutron beam diameter: 100 mm
requires large fissioning sample.
Si semiconductor detector called 'PIN diode',
active area 28.15 mm * 30.45 mm. Fragments were
identified by a double energy measurement, using 38
silicon PIN diodes assembled to two detector arrays
of 171 cm2 area each.

The energy resolution was ranged from 0.02 MeV at
En=2MeV to 27 MeV at En=450 MeV.
Several layers of different material with the
fissioning target material on top:
bottom layer (support): aluminum support, 0.5 mm
disk, outer diameter 100 mm;
next layer: Polyimide foil 51.5+-1.2 mu-g/cm2;
next layer: vacuum-deposited gold foil as
conductor: 40 mu-g/cm2;
top layer: fissioning target: UF4 applied by
'suspension spraying', diameter: 90 mm, natural
measured  Uranium content: 13.2+-2.6 mg, layer
thickness as 199.3+-3.6 mu-g/cm2 (which was used
in the  calculations rather than the nominal
207.5+-40.9 mu-g/cm2 calculated from diameter
and U-content).
Data from the author (~same data in Tbls 37-45
from thesis.
The measurement was done in the energy interval from
1 MeV till 500 MeV with variable width of the bin.
